text: Judging by this trailer, it's a bit shaky whether or not I'll see this! I was expecting this movie to be little darker, creepier, and a little intense yet still family-friendly! Something like a more light-hearted version of Trick R Treat (2007 film) or something like Jumanji meets Crimson Peak! I once wrote a treatment/mini-script for a Goosebumps movie some years ago that had an original concept but still payed homage to classic Goosebumps stories. The story/plot centered around of a group of young teenagers including a 6 year old boy,who is the little brother of the only girl of the group, who venture into the infamous woods of a fictional small sleepy town in either Massachusetts or Washington State on Halloween Night, that is told to be haunted due to the many disappearances of children who've entered into those woods. When they enter the woods, they encounter a mysterious, eerie old mansion where they are greeted a mysterious yet eccentric inventor/magician who entraps them in his sick and twisted game where they are forced to go through and survive a series of dimensions/levels that included many supernatural horrors, perils and evils in-order to escape and reclaim their freedom... If they can.  Another way I would've went with the story is that when the group of kids encounter and enter the mansion, they stumble across an ancient book in the library of the abandoned mansion and just like the actual upcoming movie, they open the book and release all the terrors and perils in the book that spread throughout the town.  That's the way I would've gone with the story if I was the director/screenwriter but that's just me! That is just my vision!The tone of my Goosebumps movie would've been a little more darker, spookier, and more intense yet still for the whole family to enjoy! Similar to films like Super 8, Jumanji, The Spiderwick Chronicles, Any of the Harry Potter films, or Hocus Pocus!

text: So... I have watched this trailer a few times now. Um... So, we see a lot of awesome references in this trailer. I was able to name a lot of them. But... So... Yeah... We see the Ferris wheel rolling after the characters... But at no point in this trailer, nor in any images I'm finding anywhere, have I seen a Horrorland Horror. I'm really hoping this is going to be a late reveal, or they don't reveal it in a trailer at all, and save the enjoyment for when we watch the movie... But it better have at least one Horrorland Horror. I say this because, aside from being my personal favorite Goosebumps creation, it is a major fan favorite. So much so that Stein decided to write a sequel, and then a Horrorland-centric series, it has been the subject of two video games, a board game, and a Tiger handheld game. It is a major icon of Goosebumps, and in a movie where they "release all" of R.L. Stein's creations, it needs a Horror. But, I will say, seeing the Ferris wheel gives me a lot of hope for that.

text: Why is everyone so excited for this? Why are you all so happy? Have you forgotten what Goosebumps was? Goosebumps was that creepy ass TV show our parents questioned on rather or not they should let us be watching. ¬†It was a series of books you could order from book fairs at your school. Every time you explored a story from R.L. Stein you experienced another dramatic horror story and what is this...........? ¬†This is surely not a horror story! No! This is Hollywood butchering my childhood once more! First Michael Bay drags Transformers out without any hope of ever seeing Unicron, then he kills TMNT. Then all the star studded power in the world could't revive that car crash they called Robo-Cop and now this.... ¬†Why are there no more people as upset about this as me? What's next? ¬† Pulp Fiction 2 without cussing? Kid friendly?

text: I feel like people( Paren'ts) suger coat EVERY FRIGGEN THING for kids now, especially in movies and tv shows like holy FLIPPEN shit!  I know and am aware that the goosebumps aren't meant to be scary or what not, but the vibe the show potrayed back in the days had a more darker, sinister, and more eerier atmosphere to it(to a kids standards), and if you were a 90's or early 2000's kid, you'd understand what I mean. The show made kids feel pretty spooked, but they were yet still be drawn to it regardless because the stories were well thought up and made you to want to keep watching.  This movie, although nostalgic because it is Goosebumps, I feel like it's going to be like every other typical kids movie out there now..  They really need to study the old shows and books better because I feel like they failed and didn't really capture what Goosebumps is all about(based on this trailer), and that is getting kids to get FRIGGEN GOOSE BUMPS!  Hope I am proved wrong.¬†  Thoughts?
